            <div type="translation">
                <p>The association of the Lycians (honours) Ptolemaios, the Chief Bodyguard (archisomatophylax) and Master of the Royal Hunt (archikynegos), the son of Ptolemaios, One of the First Friends and Master of the Royal Hunt, for his excellence and the goodwill that his father continues to show to both King Ptolemy and Queen Kleopatra, gods Epiphaneis and Eucharistoi and their children and to the association of the Lycians.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The honorand and his father were substantial figures in the Ptolemaic court: Ptolemaios and his father and the latter’s wife Agathokleia appear as beneficiaries of a ὑπέρ formula c. 187-184 in a dedication from Philae to Ptolemy V and Kleopatra I and Isis by the garrison commander Kleon (440)<!-- link to inscription --> The association (koinon) of Lycians which honoured Ptolemaios has been identified as the Lycian Federal League (so Bagnall 1976a, Lazzarini 1980) rather than a local association of Lycian soldiers such as the association of Thracian Tralleis which honoured a First Friend in 55<!-- link to inscription --> above. However Lanciers 2017 has now argued convincingly that ties between the Ptolemies and Lycia after 196 BC are at best limited  and that the koinon of Lycians should be understood here as an association of Lycian military personnel in Alexandria, comparable to the association of Thracian Tralleis in 55<!-- link to inscription -->.</p>
            </div>
